FBIS3-18820 "drweu046__a94052" FBIS-WEU-94-046-A Document Type:Daily Report 9 March 1994 ANNEX Italy & Vatican City January Trade Balance, Exports Viewed BR0703135294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1226 GMT 5 Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY BR0703135294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database Language: English Article Type:BFN [Unattributed article: "Italy's Trade Balance in Red Outside European Union"] [Text] Rome, 5 Mar (ANSA) -- Italy's trade balance with countries outside the European Union dipped into the red in January, a month which is traditionally bad for Italian trade, while over all exports rose 13.1 percent against a 4.5 percent increase in imports, according to the national statistics bureau ISTAT [Central Statistics Institute]. Last January, Italian exports outside the European Union totaled 8.864 trillion lire (5.26 million dollars), while imports were valued at 9.056 trillion lire (5.374 billion dollars). On a sector-by-sector basis, transport means showed the worst performance with a 34-percent plunge in exports. ISTAT noted, however, that by excluding ship sales there was actually a 19 percent increase in sale abroad. The following table, expressed in billion European lira, with one dollar worth 1,685 lire Friday [4 March], compares Italy's exports to various areas of the world in 1993 and 1994: ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | |1993 |1994 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |European Free Trade Agre-|- 199 |- 306 | |ement area | | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Central and East Europe |- 251 |- 261 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |OPEC |- 497 |- 547 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |United States |+ 79 |+ 464 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |China |- 156 |- 204 | ---------